<collectingCountry box="[415,519,266,292]" name="Thailand" pageId="22" pageNumber="227">Thailand</collectingCountry>
in 
<bibRefCitation author="HUTSON, A. M. &amp; S. P. MICKLEBURGH &amp; P. A. RACEY" bookContentInfo="258 pp." journalOrPublisher="IUCN, Gland" pageId="22" pageNumber="227" refId="ref22236" refString="HUTSON, A. M., S. P. MICKLEBURGH, and P. A. RACEY. 2001. Microchiropteran bats: global status sur- vey and conservation action plan. IUCN, Gland, 258 pp." title="Microchiropteran bats: global status sur- vey and conservation action plan" type="book" year="2001">Hutson et al. (2001)</bibRefCitation>
, according to A. M. Hutson (pers. comm, 2004) the inclusion of Thai- land is an error.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="22" pageNumber="227" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="22.[130,643,163,1736]" box="[130,398,438,464]" pageId="22" pageNumber="227">
<emphasis box="[130,398,438,464]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="227">Descriptive characters</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="22.[130,643,163,1736]" pageId="22" pageNumber="227">
Only known by the 
<typeStatus box="[427,533,472,498]" pageId="22" pageNumber="227">holotype</typeStatus>
, this ap- pears to be a rather large species with a forearm length of 35.0 mm (
<tableCitation box="[484,576,540,567]" captionStart="TABLE" captionStartId="7.[130,143,167,188]" captionTargetId="graphics@7.[127,1200,376,1322]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="TABLE 4. External and bacular measurements (in mm) and body mass (in g) of 21 species of Vespertilionidae recorded from Myanmar, including the lengths of head and body (HB), tail (TAIL), foot (HF), tibia (TIBIA), forearm (FA), fifth, fourth, third metacarpal (5MET, 4MET and 3MET), ear (E), and baculum (BAC LGT). Sample sizes for males and females differing from those reported under n are given in parentheses after the measurement. Mean and SD are included when sample size is 3 or more. Data in italics are based on specimens collected outside Myanmar. Species listed in order of genera, and taxonomic groups and subgroups based on Corbet and Hill (1992) and Bates and Harrison (1997)" pageId="22" pageNumber="227">Table 4</tableCitation>
). The single male specimen has a tuft of glandular hairs radiating from a point close to the base of the tail on the upper surface of the interfemoral membrane. The tuft is about 
<quantity box="[130,214,712,738]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.2" pageId="22" pageNumber="227" unit="mm" value="12.0">12 mm</quantity>
in diameter, with the hairs 
<quantity box="[544,643,711,738]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.5" metricValueMax="6.0" metricValueMin="5.0" pageId="22" pageNumber="227" unit="mm" value="5.5" valueMax="6.0" valueMin="5.0">5–6 mm</quantity>
in length, uniformly brown and more or less unctuous or sticky. Although 
<bibRefCitation author="THOMAS, O." journalOrPublisher="Journal of the Bom- bay Natural History Society" pageId="22" pageNumber="227" pagination="29 - 36" part="24" refId="ref23343" refString="THOMAS, O. 1915 b. On pipistrelles of the genera Pipistrellus and Scotozous. Journal of the Bom- bay Natural History Society, 24: 29 - 36." title="On pipistrelles of the genera Pipistrellus and Scotozous" type="journal article" year="1915">
Thomas (1915 
<emphasis box="[198,213,814,840]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="227">b</emphasis>
)
</bibRefCitation>
had written that the ‘penis [is] skinned in the type, so that it is doubtful whether it has a bone or not’, the baculum of the 
<typeStatus box="[204,307,916,942]" pageId="22" pageNumber="227">holotype</typeStatus>
was subsequently illustrated in 
<bibRefCitation author="HILL, J. E. &amp; D. L HARRISON" box="[160,455,951,977]" journalOrPublisher="Bulletin of the British Museum Natural History (Zoology)" pageId="22" pageNumber="227" pagination="225 - 305" part="52" refId="ref22004" refString="HILL, J. E., and D. L HARRISON. 1987. The baculum in the Vespertilioninae (Chiroptera: Vespertilionidae) with a systematic review, a synopsis of Pipistrellus and Eptesicus, and the descriptions of a new genus and subgenus. Bulletin of the British Museum Natural History (Zoology), 52: 225 - 305." title="The baculum in the Vespertilioninae (Chiroptera: Vespertilionidae) with a systematic review, a synopsis of Pipistrellus and Eptesicus, and the descriptions of a new genus and subgenus" type="journal article" year="1987">Hill and Harrison (1987)</bibRefCitation>
. Approximately 
<quantity box="[130,219,985,1011]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.6" pageId="22" pageNumber="227" unit="mm" value="2.6">2.6 mm</quantity>
in length, it has a flat, spoon-shaped tip, which is deflected downwards; a straight shaft and a simple broad base (Fig. 1E). The skin of the 
<typeStatus box="[365,468,1087,1113]" pageId="22" pageNumber="227">holotype</typeStatus>
has long, silky fur which is a deep rich brown with the hair bases almost black on the dorsal surface. The hair tips on the ventral surface are a mid-brown with almost black roots. The braincase is fairly high at the occiput, with a slight frontal depression when viewed lat- erally. The zygomata are robust, each has a well developed postorbital process. The rostrum is moderate in length, not broad- ened, and without a median rostral depres- sion. The basioccipital region has a well de- fined central ridge running between the two cochleae and deep basisphenoid pits. The first (I2) and second (I3) upper incisors both have secondary cusps and are well devel- oped teeth. The first upper premolar (P2) is about equal to two-thirds of the crown area of I2. The first lower premolar (P) is
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="22.[130,643,163,1736]" lastBlockId="22.[686,1199,163,1176]" pageId="22" pageNumber="227">2 between half and two-thirds the crown area of the second (P4).</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="22" pageNumber="227" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="22.[686,1199,163,1176]" box="[686,865,265,291]" pageId="22" pageNumber="227">
<emphasis box="[686,865,265,291]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="227">Similar species</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="22.[686,1199,163,1176]" pageId="22" pageNumber="227">Distinguished from all other local pip- istrelle species by the presence of the tuft at the base of the tail and by the shape of the baculum.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="22.[686,1199,163,1176]" box="[686,883,470,495]" pageId="22" pageNumber="227">
<emphasis box="[686,883,470,495]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="227">Taxonomic notes</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="22.[686,1199,163,1176]" pageId="22" pageNumber="227">
According to 
<bibRefCitation author="FRANCIS, C. M. &amp; J. E. HILL" box="[900,1194,503,530]" journalOrPublisher="Mammalia" pageId="22" pageNumber="227" pagination="43 - 55" part="50" refId="ref21680" refString="FRANCIS, C. M., and J. E. HILL. 1986. A review of the Bornean Pipistrellus (Mammalia: Chiroptera). Mammalia, 50: 43 - 55." title="A review of the Bornean Pipistrellus (Mammalia: Chiroptera)" type="journal article" year="1986">Francis and Hill (1986)</bibRefCitation>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Thomas" authorityYear="1915" box="[686,818,538,564]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Pipistrellus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="227" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="lophurus">
<emphasis box="[686,818,538,564]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="227">P. lophurus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
may be conspecific with 
<emphasis box="[1118,1198,538,564]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="227">
<emphasis box="[686,733,572,597]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="227">kitcheneri</emphasis>
</emphasis>
, in which case 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Thomas" authorityYear="1915" box="[926,1030,572,598]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Pipistrellus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="227" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="lophurus">
<emphasis box="[926,1030,572,598]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="227">lophurus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
would be the prior name (
<bibRefCitation author="CORBET, G. B. &amp; J. E. HILL" bookContentInfo="488 pp." box="[835,1108,606,632]" journalOrPublisher="Natural History Mu- seum Publications. Oxford University, Oxford" pageId="22" pageNumber="227" refId="ref21372" refString="CORBET, G. B., and J. E. HILL. 1992. The mammals of the Indomalayan region. Natural History Mu- seum Publications. Oxford University, Oxford, 488 pp." title="The mammals of the Indomalayan region." type="book" year="1992">Corbet and Hill, 1992</bibRefCitation>
). However, the bacula of the two taxa are morphologically distinct (
<bibRefCitation author="HILL, J. E. &amp; D. L HARRISON" journalOrPublisher="Bulletin of the British Museum Natural History (Zoology)" pageId="22" pageNumber="227" pagination="225 - 305" part="52" refId="ref22004" refString="HILL, J. E., and D. L HARRISON. 1987. The baculum in the Vespertilioninae (Chiroptera: Vespertilionidae) with a systematic review, a synopsis of Pipistrellus and Eptesicus, and the descriptions of a new genus and subgenus. Bulletin of the British Museum Natural History (Zoology), 52: 225 - 305." title="The baculum in the Vespertilioninae (Chiroptera: Vespertilionidae) with a systematic review, a synopsis of Pipistrellus and Eptesicus, and the descriptions of a new genus and subgenus" type="journal article" year="1987">Hill and Harrison, 1987</bibRefCitation>
) and the two taxa are treated as distinct species by 
<bibRefCitation author="CORBET, G. B. &amp; J. E. HILL" bookContentInfo="488 pp." box="[876,1150,742,768]" journalOrPublisher="Natural History Mu- seum Publications. Oxford University, Oxford" pageId="22" pageNumber="227" refId="ref21372" refString="CORBET, G. B., and J. E. HILL. 1992. The mammals of the Indomalayan region. Natural History Mu- seum Publications. Oxford University, Oxford, 488 pp." title="The mammals of the Indomalayan region." type="book" year="1992">Corbet and Hill (1992)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="22" pageNumber="227" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="22.[686,1199,163,1176]" box="[686,782,810,836]" pageId="22" pageNumber="227">
<emphasis box="[686,782,810,836]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="227">Ecology</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="22.[686,1199,163,1176]" pageId="22" pageNumber="227">
In Tanintharyi Division, a single specimen was collected from Maliwun, which is a township at the head of a small tributary flowing into the Pakchan River. According to 
<bibRefCitation author="Wroughton" box="[726,971,979,1006]" firstAuthor="Wroughton" pageId="22" pageNumber="227" pagination="88 - 89" refId="ref20981" refString="Natural History Society, 29: 88 - 89. WROUGHTON, R. C. 1915 b. Bombay Natural History" type="journal article" year="1915" yearSuffix="b">
Wroughton (1915 
<emphasis box="[945,960,980,1006]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="227">b</emphasis>
)
</bibRefCitation>
, the area around Maliwun had been cleared (‘Taungya’ clearings) and was under grass with ‘a more or less open, park like appearance’. The grasslands were surrounded by ‘evergreen jungle’.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
